    Mirror solutions 
  
The picture looks quite unexpected. One has equivalent geometry on
both sides of the mirror line , produced by the standard scalar
field in the region II, while the same geometry in the region I is
produced by a ghost.  Technically this happens because the pure
imaginary transformation of the scalar field  into 
produces a real scalar field in a mirror region.  It is tempting to
call such scalar fields as mirror-ghosts. A different pair of scalar
fields which solve the equation () and have the mirror
ghost properties are  and 
.

